<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<configuration>
  <!--
    Supply-chain hardening for package restore (audit finding L1).

    <clear/> drops any machine/user-level <packageSources> so the resolved feed set is
    exactly what this file declares — a developer's global NuGet.config cannot silently add
    a second feed that introduces a dependency-confusion / source-substitution path.

    packageSourceMapping binds every package id (the "*" pattern) to nuget.org. If a private
    or internal feed is ever added later, package ids must be mapped to it explicitly; an
    attacker publishing a same-named package to nuget.org cannot get it resolved for an id
    that is mapped elsewhere. This is the primary defense against dependency confusion.

    NOTE ON SIGNATURE VALIDATION: signatureValidationMode=require + <trustedSigners> was
    evaluated and deliberately NOT enabled. Trusting only the current nuget.org repository
    cert breaks restore on older packages still carrying a pre-rotation repository
    countersignature (e.g. System.Security.Cryptography.ProtectedData 4.5.0 -> NU3034), and
    the enforcement differs by OS (passes on macOS, fails on Linux/Docker), so it is too
    brittle to gate the build on. Tamper detection is already provided by the committed
    packages.lock.json content hashes combined with locked-mode restore: a package whose
    bytes differ from the locked hash fails restore regardless of signatures.
  -->
  <packageSources>
    <clear />
    <add key="nuget.org" value="https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json" protocolVersion="3" />
  </packageSources>

  <packageSourceMapping>
    <packageSource key="nuget.org">
      <package pattern="*" />
    </packageSource>
  </packageSourceMapping>
</configuration>
